{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508049","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508049"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:01:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:01:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2709"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2709","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2709"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.15,0.03,0.74,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2709"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103608"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2709","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2709"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2709"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86025"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"188"},{"type":"tags","id":"191"},{"type":"tags","id":"225"},{"type":"tags","id":"1108"},{"type":"tags","id":"1111"},{"type":"tags","id":"1150"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"3180"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5184"},{"type":"tags","id":"5185"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3405"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3407"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7419"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27026"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36806"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103608","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103608"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 19-year-old woman is admitted involuntarily to the psychiatry inpatient ward with a six-month history of behavioural disturbance and impaired social functioning. According to her new housemate, she moved across the country in an attempt to escape pursuit by an international criminal gang. Recently, she destroyed all of her electronic devices with a hammer as she believes they were being used to record her activities. She reports often hearing the voices of her enemies outside her bedroom window. She has not left the house in over a month and has stopped showering. She denies suicidal or homicidal ideation. She does not have any significant psychiatric history, however her medical history includes obesity and hypertension. On examination, she appears anxious and is poorly groomed. Her BMI is 34 kg/m2. Urine drug screening returns a negative result.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate antipsychotic to commence in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Clozapine","Olanzapine","Droperidol","Aripiprazole","Chlorpromazine"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has presented with symptoms consistent with psychosis. Given that she has been experiencing these symptoms for 6 months and that there is no evidence of organic pathology or substance abuse, the most likely diagnosis is schizophrenia. As such, she requires an antipsychotic agent to help control her symptoms, which have quite clearly caused significant impairment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAripiprazole\u003C/strong\u003E is a second-generation antipsychotic with a unique mechanism of action as a partial dopamine agonist. It has a favorable metabolic side effect profile compared to many other antipsychotics, with minimal weight gain, less impact on glucose metabolism, and minimal effects on prolactin levels. Given this patient\u0027s pre-existing obesity and hypertension, aripiprazole is an appropriate choice as it is less likely to exacerbate these conditions compared to other antipsychotics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOlanzapine\u003C/strong\u003E is another second-generation antipsychotic agent. It has proven efficacy in the treatment of primary psychotic disorders, however is associated with a number of metabolic side effects including weight gain, impaired glucose tolerance and hyperlipidaemia. Given that this patient has a BMI of 34, it is inappropriate to start an agent that will likely worsen her metabolic profile even further. As such, olanzapine is not the best answer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDroperidol\u003C/strong\u003E is a first-generation antipsychotic. Sometimes used in clinical settings for patients with nausea and vomiting, or challenging behaviour not responding to other therapies, this agent is associated with a number of side effects. The most common side effects are sedation, prolonged QT interval and extra-pyradmidal side effects including Parkinsonism, dystonia, akathisia and tardive dyskinesia. Generally speaking, patients requiring long-term antipsychotic therapy for a primary psychotic disorder such as schizophrenia will be commenced on one of the newer second-generation medications. The reason for this is that their side effect profile is less severe and the patient preference is greater. Due to this, droperidol is an incorrect answer option.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClozapine\u003C/strong\u003E is known to be an extremely effective antipsychotic and can be highly useful in cases of psychosis refractory to other agents, however it is associated with a number of serious side effects including agranulocytosis, myocarditis and paralytic ileus. Prescription of this drug requires intensive monitoring in the initial stages of therapy, as well as ongoing monitoring once stable plasma concentrations have been reached. For all of these reasons, patients are only eligible to receive treatment with clozapine once two other antipsychotic agents have been trialled and found to be unsuccessful. As such, clozapine is an incorrect answer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChlorpromazine\u003C/strong\u003E is an older first-generation antipsychotic. For similar reasons to droperidol, it is not the most suitable agent to commence first-line in schizophrenia. It has significant side effects including sedation, orthostatic hypotension, and anticholinergic effects, as well as a high risk of extrapyramidal symptoms. As such, it is not the correct answer.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Aripiprazole is a second-generation antipsychotic with a favorable metabolic side effect profile, making it suitable for patients with obesity and hypertension.","Second-generation antipsychotics are generally preferred over first-generation antipsychotics due to a more favourable side effect profile, including fewer extrapyramidal symptoms.","The choice of antipsychotic should consider the patient\u0027s comorbidities and potential side effect profiles."],"references":["Lin CC, Bai YM, Wang YC, Chen TT, Lai IC, Chen JY, Chen SY, Gau SS, Liou YJ. Improved body weight and metabolic outcomes in overweight or obese psychiatric patients switched to amisulpride from other atypical antipsychotics. J Clin Psychopharmacol. 2009 Dec;29(6):529-36. doi: 10.1097/JCP.0b013e3181bf613e. PMID: 19910716. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19910716/","Nuss P, Hummer M, Tessier C. The use of amisulpride in the treatment of acute psychosis. Ther Clin Risk Manag. 2007 Mar;3(1):3-11. doi: 10.2147/tcrm.2007.3.1.3. PMID: 18360610; PMCID: PMC1936283. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC1936283/","Curran MP, Perry CM. Amisulpride: a review of its use in the management of schizophrenia. Drugs. 2001;61(14):2123-50. doi: 10.2165/00003495-200161140-00014. PMID: 11735643. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11735643/","Howard R, Cort E, Bradley R, Harper E, Kelly L, Bentham P, Ritchie C, Reeves S, Fawzi W, Livingston G, Sommerlad A, Oomman S, Nazir E, Nilforooshan R, Barber R, Fox C, Macharouthu A, Ramachandra P, Pattan V, Sykes J, Curran V, Katona C, Dening T, Knapp M, Romeo R, Gray R. Amisulpride for very late-onset schizophrenia-like psychosis: the ATLAS three-arm RCT. Health Technol Assess. 2018 Nov;22(67):1-62. doi: 10.3310/hta22670. PMID: 30507375; PMCID: PMC6304731. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30507375/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86025"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2709"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86025","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86025"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-24T16:13:45+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-24T16:15:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2709"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103608"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships"